          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "In this section, we present the proof of the theorem.",
        "block_bbox": [
          86,
          106,
          539,
          140
        ],
        "block_id": 2,
        "block_order": 2,
        "group_id": 2,
        "global_block_id": 255,
        "global_group_id": 255,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            85.55242919921875,
            112.14080047607422
          ],
          [
            537.976806640625,
            104.60039520263672
          ],
          [
            538.449951171875,
            132.99249267578125
          ],
          [
            86.02557373046875,
            140.53289794921875
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "Theorem 4.2. Suppose the DDIM model can learn a parameter  $ \\nu $ such that, for any  $ x \\sim \\mathcal{D}_{training} $ with dimension  $ d $, the prediction error  $ \\epsilon - \\epsilon_0 (\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t} x + \\sqrt{1 - \\bar{\\alpha}_t} \\epsilon, t) $ is a random variable  $ X = (X_1, X_2, \\ldots, X_d) $ with zero expectation and finite cumulant-generating function for each coordinate (Durret, 2010). Suppose the sampling interval  $ k $ is equal to the variation API diffusion step  $ t $. Let  $ \\hat{x} $ be the average of  $ n $ output images of  $ x $ using the variation API. Then we have",
        "block_bbox": [
          86,
          145,
          1137,
          262
        ],
        "block_id": 3,
        "block_order": 3,
        "group_id": 3,
        "global_block_id": 256,
        "global_group_id": 256,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            86.0,
            153.0
          ],
          [
            1136.0,
            153.0
          ],
          [
            1136.0,
            261.0
          ],
          [
            86.0,
            261.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "display_formula",
        "block_content": " $$ \\mathbb{P}(\\|\\hat{x}-x\\|\\geq\\beta)\\leq d\\exp\\left(-n\\min_{i}\\Psi_{X_{i}}^{*}\\left(\\frac{\\beta\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}{\\sqrt{d(1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t})}}\\right)\\right), $$ ",
        "block_bbox": [
          344,
          274,
          882,
          352
        ],
        "block_id": 4,
        "block_order": 4,
        "group_id": 4,
        "global_block_id": 257,
        "global_group_id": 257,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            344.0,
            274.0
          ],
          [
            882.0,
            274.0
          ],
          [
            882.0,
            352.0
          ],
          [
            344.0,
            352.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "where  $ \\beta > 0 $ and  $ \\Psi_{X_i}^* $ is the Fenchel-Legendre dual of the cumulant-generating function  $ \\Psi_{X_i} $.",
        "block_bbox": [
          90,
          370,
          893,
          402
        ],
        "block_id": 5,
        "block_order": 5,
        "group_id": 5,
        "global_block_id": 258,
        "global_group_id": 258,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            90.0,
            370.0
          ],
          [
            893.0,
            370.0
          ],
          [
            893.0,
            402.0
          ],
          [
            90.0,
            402.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "Proof. We denote  $ x^i $ as the  $ i $-th output image of  $ x $ using the variation API. We denote the  $ i $-th Gaussian noise as  $ \\epsilon^i $ and the forward process yields  $ x_t^i = \\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t} x + \\sqrt{1 - \\bar{\\alpha}_t} \\epsilon^i $.",
        "block_bbox": [
          92,
          430,
          1132,
          489
        ],
        "block_id": 6,
        "block_order": 6,
        "group_id": 6,
        "global_block_id": 259,
        "global_group_id": 259,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            92.0,
            430.0
          ],
          [
            1132.0,
            430.0
          ],
          [
            1132.0,
            489.0
          ],
          [
            92.0,
            489.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "As the sampling interval is equal to the variation API diffusion step t, we have",
        "block_bbox": [
          92,
          501,
          763,
          530
        ],
        "block_id": 7,
        "block_order": 7,
        "group_id": 7,
        "global_block_id": 260,
        "global_group_id": 260,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            92.0,
            501.0
          ],
          [
            763.0,
            501.0
          ],
          [
            763.0,
            530.0
          ],
          [
            92.0,
            530.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "display_formula",
        "block_content": " $$ \\begin{align*}x^{i}-x&=\\frac{x^{i}_{t}-\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon_{\\theta}(\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}x+\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon^{i},t)}{\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}-x,\\\\&=\\frac{\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}x+\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon^{i}-\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon_{\\theta}(\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}x+\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon^{i},t)}{\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}-x,\\\\&=\\frac{\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}{\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}(\\epsilon^{i}-\\epsilon_{\\theta}(\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}x+\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}\\epsilon^{i},t)).\\end{align*} $$ ",
        "block_bbox": [
          295,
          545,
          930,
          742
        ],
        "block_id": 8,
        "block_order": 8,
        "group_id": 8,
        "global_block_id": 261,
        "global_group_id": 261,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            295.0,
            545.0
          ],
          [
            930.0,
            545.0
          ],
          [
            930.0,
            742.0
          ],
          [
            295.0,
            742.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "If we denote the random variable  $ X^i = (X_1^i, X_2^i, \\ldots, X_d^i) $ represents  $ \\epsilon^i - \\epsilon_\\theta(\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t}x + \\sqrt{1 - \\bar{\\alpha}_t}\\epsilon^i, t) $, then we consider  $ S_n^i = \\sum_{j=1}^n X_j^i $. From the assumption we know that all the  $ X_j^i $ are i.i.d. random variables (with the same distribution of  $ X_i $ in Theorem 4.2) with zero expectation and finite cumulant-generating function  $ \\Psi_{X_i}(s) = \\log E[e^{sX_i}] < +\\infty $. Using the theorem of Cramér–Chernoff method for sums of i.i.d. random variables (Durret, 2010), we get the following probability inequality for any  $ \\beta > 0 $:",
        "block_bbox": [
          91,
          801,
          1137,
          952
        ],
        "block_id": 9,
        "block_order": 9,
        "group_id": 9,
        "global_block_id": 262,
        "global_group_id": 262,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            90.0422592163086,
            808.0064086914062
          ],
          [
            1136.0001220703125,
            801.0000610351562
          ],
          [
            1136.9578857421875,
            943.9935913085938
          ],
          [
            91.0,
            950.9999389648438
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "display_formula",
        "block_content": " $$ \\mathbb{P}(|S_{n}^{i}|\\geq\\beta)\\leq\\exp(-n\\Psi_{X_{i}}^{*}(\\frac{\\beta}{n})), $$ ",
        "block_bbox": [
          460,
          965,
          767,
          1021
        ],
        "block_id": 10,
        "block_order": 10,
        "group_id": 10,
        "global_block_id": 263,
        "global_group_id": 263,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            460.0,
            965.0
          ],
          [
            767.0,
            965.0
          ],
          [
            767.0,
            1021.0
          ],
          [
            460.0,
            1021.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "where  $ \\beta > 0 $ and  $ \\Psi_{X_i}^*(y) = \\sup_{s > 0}(sy - \\Psi_{X_i}(s)) $ is the Fenchel-Legendre dual of the cumulant-generating function  $ \\Psi_{X_i} $. Therefore, denote  $ S_n = (S_n^1, S_n^2, \\ldots, S_n^d) $, taking the definition of  $ \\|\\hat{x} - x\\| = \\left\\|\\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{i=1}^n (x^i - x)\\right\\| = \\frac{\\sqrt{1 - \\hat{\\alpha}_i}}{n \\sqrt{\\hat{\\alpha}_i}}\\|S_n\\| $, we get the following bound of the reconstruction error:",
        "block_bbox": [
          90,
          1034,
          1139,
          1146
        ],
        "block_id": 11,
        "block_order": 11,
        "group_id": 11,
        "global_block_id": 264,
        "global_group_id": 264,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            90.0,
            1034.0
          ],
          [
            1139.0,
            1034.0
          ],
          [
            1139.0,
            1146.0
          ],
          [
            90.0,
            1146.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "display_formula",
        "block_content": " $$ \\mathbb{P}(\\|\\hat{x}-x\\|\\geq\\beta)\\leq\\sum_{i=1}^{d}P(|S_{n}^{i}|\\geq\\frac{n\\beta\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}{\\sqrt{d(1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t})}})\\leq d\\exp(-n\\min_{i}\\Psi_{X_{i}}^{*}(\\frac{\\beta\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_{t}}}{\\sqrt{d(1-\\bar{\\alpha}_{t})}})), $$ ",
        "block_bbox": [
          233,
          1163,
          998,
